### Steps to reproduce

1. Configure a OAuth provider like [Google](https://feathersjs.com/cookbook/authentication/google.html) in the api (reproduced with Google & Microsoft)
2. Create a "Login Using Google" button that links to /oauth/google on a client website
3. Run the client website
4. Click the "Login Using Google" button
5. Login to your Google account
6. User is redirected back to the api which authenticates the user
7. Api then tries to redirect to https://accounts.google.com/ which results in the error `Referer "https://accounts.google.com/" is not allowed.`

### Expected behavior

Api should redirect back to the client website which triggered the login via a "Login Using Google" button

### Actual behavior

Api tries to redirect to https://accounts.google.com/

### System configuration

Feathers version: 5.0.0-pre.35

### Workaround
I'm able to workaround this by clearing the `referer` in a custom OAuth strategy, the api then uses the first url in the `origins` list in the configuration as the redirect url
```
class OAuthRefererStrategy extends OAuthStrategy {
  async getRedirect(
    data: AuthenticationResult | Error,
    params?: AuthenticationParams
  ): Promise<string | null> {
    if (params?.headers?.referer) {
      params.headers.referer = undefined;
    }
    return super.getRedirect(data, params);
  }
}
```

